Bombarder in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of the main assets of American president Barack Obama.
It seems, however, that his words have now trapped him.
After saying last March that the United States « would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people » and mentioning last year a « red line » that should not be crossed, Obama would lose face if he does not respond strongly to the killing of over 1,000 civilians attributed to the Syrian regime using sarin gas.
Obviously, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama resort to such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
US Secretary of State John Kerry is right to call the use of chemical weapons "morally repulsive."
But torturing children, the precursors of civil war two years ago, is just as morally repulsive.
And is killing civilians with chemical weapons morally more repulsive than bombing them, shooting them, or starving them to death?
It is commonly accepted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Mass destruction weapons, especially the nuclear bomb, certainly cause more damage and more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing approximately 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
A viewpoint, notably defended by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, argues that a swift punitive action could convince President Syrian Bashar al-Assad to abandon the use of chemical weapons and return to « more ordinary means for massacring his people ».
I think that makes no sense.
The question is surely about the massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral indignation, justified as it may be, is not a sufficient reason for going to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the death of more than 40 million Chinese people in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sensible person has suggested that a military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is this therefore a legal question? The use of chemical weapons constitutes a clear violation of international conventions, including the Chemical Weapons Convention, which Syria has never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, which it is a party to.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad as a war criminal, in which case he should be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, by the way, by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not a policy easily defendable.
One could however argue that the "international community", or Western countries, or the United States as the main Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn away when innocent people are mass murdered?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where should we draw the line?
How many murders constitute a genocide?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Or is the number even irrelevant?
After all, genocide is a matter of intent; there is a will to kill or to persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic affiliation, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to reflect on before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance to improve the situation, to save lives, and to make the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Responding to this requires asking: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Like the action of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" is more likely to produce results in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a major power.
No one would consider missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of human rights or to enforce international humanitarian law and conventions.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is not a major power either.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving more significant countries, including Iran, Turkey and Russia.
There is no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is by no means certain that a U.S. intervention would reduce the risk of a broader conflict.
In fact, some proponents of a U.S. intervention – both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks" – seem to desire the opposite: they are calling for a war with Iran.
And Obama has probably established a link in his mind between the red line regarding Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
So what can we expect from U.S. strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they are not intended to topple the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But a single missile would make the United States a direct participant in this war, causing a resurgence of violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly prudent.
This viewpoint is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And of a majority of Americans.
It may even be Obama's view, which is why he is desperately trying to buy time by delegating to the U.S. Congress the authority to use military force in Syria.
Since taking office, his relationship with Congress has hardly been easy.
But he needs it more than ever to cover his back.
